# Essential to know
- TypeScript = JavaScript + Types
- Catches errors before runtime
- Better IDE autocomplete and refactoring
- Compiles to JavaScript

---

# TypeScript: JavaScript with Superpowers

## What is TypeScript?

**TypeScript** is JavaScript with **type annotations**. It helps catch bugs early!

**JavaScript (no types):**
```javascript
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

add(5, '10'); // '510' (bug!)
```

**TypeScript (with types):**
```typescript
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}

add(5, '10'); // âŒ Error: '10' is not a number
```

## Why Use TypeScript?

**1. Catch Errors Early**
```typescript
const user = { name: 'Alice', age: 25 };

console.log(user.email); // âŒ Error: Property 'email' doesn't exist
```

JavaScript would only show this error at runtime!

**2. Better Autocomplete**

Your IDE knows exactly what properties and methods exist:
```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email: string;
}

const user: User = { name: 'Alice', age: 25, email: 'alice@example.com' };
user. // IDE shows: name, age, email
```

**3. Safer Refactoring**

Change a type in one place, TypeScript shows all places that break.

**4. Self-Documenting Code**
```typescript
// Types serve as documentation
function createUser(
  name: string,
  age: number,
  isAdmin: boolean
): User {
  // ...
}
```

## Basic Types

```typescript
let name: string = 'Alice';
let age: number = 25;
let isActive: boolean = true;
let numbers: number[] = [1, 2, 3];
let tuple: [string, number] = ['Alice', 25];
let anything: any = 'can be anything'; // Avoid this!
```

## Interfaces & Types

**Interface:**
```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  age?: number; // Optional
}

const user: User = {
  id: 1,
  name: 'Alice',
  email: 'alice@example.com'
};
```

**Type Alias:**
```typescript
type Status = 'pending' | 'active' | 'inactive';
type ID = string | number;

let userStatus: Status = 'active';
let userId: ID = 123;
```

## Function Types

```typescript
// Function with typed parameters and return
function greet(name: string): string {
  return `Hello ${name}`;
}

// Arrow function
const add = (a: number, b: number): number => a + b;

// Optional parameters
function log(message: string, prefix?: string): void {
  console.log(prefix ? `${prefix}: ${message}` : message);
}
```

## Generics

```typescript
// Works with any type
function identity<T>(value: T): T {
  return value;
}

identity<string>('hello'); // 'hello'
identity<number>(42);      // 42

// Generic interfaces
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T;
  status: number;
  error?: string;
}

const userResponse: ApiResponse<User> = {
  data: { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
  status: 200
};
```

## TypeScript vs JavaScript

**JavaScript:**
- âœ… Simpler, less code
- âœ… No build step needed
- âŒ Runtime errors
- âŒ Harder to refactor

**TypeScript:**
- âœ… Catches errors early
- âœ… Better tooling
- âœ… Easier to maintain
- âŒ Needs compilation
- âŒ More verbose

## Do You Need TypeScript?

**Yes, if:**
- âœ… Large codebase
- âœ… Team project
- âœ… Long-term project
- âœ… You want better tooling

**Maybe not, if:**
- âŒ Small script
- âŒ Prototype
- âŒ Solo learning project

lessons.codeExample:
// TypeScript example: Building a type-safe API

// Define data types
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  role: 'admin' | 'user';
}

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  content: string;
  authorId: number;
  published: boolean;
}

type ApiResponse<T> = 
  | { success: true; data: T }
  | { success: false; error: string };

// Type-safe API functions
async function getUser(id: number): Promise<ApiResponse<User>> {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
    const user = await response.json();
    return { success: true, data: user };
  } catch (error) {
    return { success: false, error: 'Failed to fetch user' };
  }
}

async function createPost(
  title: string,
  content: string,
  authorId: number
): Promise<ApiResponse<Post>> {
  const post: Omit<Post, 'id'> = {
    title,
    content,
    authorId,
    published: false
  };

  try {
    const response = await fetch('/api/posts', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(post)
    });
    const newPost = await response.json();
    return { success: true, data: newPost };
  } catch (error) {
    return { success: false, error: 'Failed to create post' };
  }
}

// Usage with type safety
const result = await getUser(1);
if (result.success) {
  console.log(result.data.name); // TypeScript knows this is a User
} else {
  console.error(result.error);
}

