# Essential to know
- Types prevent entire categories of bugs
- Types make code self-documenting
- Types enable better tooling (autocomplete, refactoring)
- Types don't slow down runtime (only compile time)

---

# Why Types Matter

## The Problem with Dynamic Typing

**JavaScript without types:**
```javascript
function calculateTotal(items) {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
}

// Works fine
calculateTotal([{ price: 10 }, { price: 20 }]); // 30

// Runtime error! 
calculateTotal([{ cost: 10 }]); // NaN (item.price is undefined)
calculateTotal(null); // TypeError: Cannot read property 'reduce'
```

You only discover these bugs when the code runs!

## Types Catch Bugs at Compile Time

**TypeScript with types:**
```typescript
interface Item {
  price: number;
}

function calculateTotal(items: Item[]): number {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
}

calculateTotal([{ cost: 10 }]); // âŒ Error: Property 'price' is missing
calculateTotal(null); // âŒ Error: Argument of type 'null' is not assignable
```

Bugs caught **before** runtime!

## Types as Documentation

**Without types (unclear):**
```javascript
function createUser(data) {
  // What is data? What properties?
  // What gets returned?
}
```

**With types (clear):**
```typescript
interface UserInput {
  name: string;
  email: string;
  age?: number;
}

interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  age: number;
  createdAt: Date;
}

function createUser(data: UserInput): User {
  // Crystal clear what goes in and comes out
}
```

## Types Enable Refactoring

**Scenario:** Rename `email` to `emailAddress`

**JavaScript:** ğŸ˜°
- Search for all `user.email`
- Might miss some
- Might break things
- Find out at runtime

**TypeScript:** ğŸ˜Š
- Rename in interface
- TypeScript shows all errors
- Fix them all
- Guaranteed to work

## Types Prevent Common Mistakes

**1. Null/Undefined:**
```typescript
function greet(name: string) {
  console.log(`Hello ${name.toUpperCase()}`);
}

greet(undefined); // âŒ Error caught!
```

**2. Wrong Property:**
```typescript
const user = { name: 'Alice', age: 25 };
console.log(user.email); // âŒ Error: Property 'email' doesn't exist
```

**3. Wrong Type:**
```typescript
function add(a: number, b: number) {
  return a + b;
}

add('5', '10'); // âŒ Error: String is not assignable to number
```

**4. Missing Required Fields:**
```typescript
interface Config {
  apiKey: string;
  endpoint: string;
}

const config: Config = {
  apiKey: 'abc123'
  // âŒ Error: Property 'endpoint' is missing
};
```

## Types Improve IDE Experience

**Autocomplete:**
Type `user.` and see all available properties

**Go to Definition:**
Jump to where a type is defined

**Rename Symbol:**
Rename all occurrences safely

**Error Detection:**
See errors as you type, not at runtime

## Real-World Impact

**Study findings:**
- TypeScript prevents ~15% of bugs
- 38% of bugs on GitHub could be prevented by types
- Teams report 30-50% fewer runtime errors

## When Types Aren't Needed

**Skip types for:**
- âŒ One-off scripts
- âŒ Quick prototypes
- âŒ Very simple projects
- âŒ Learning basic programming

**Use types for:**
- âœ… Production code
- âœ… Team projects
- âœ… Long-term projects
- âœ… Libraries/packages

## The Cost of Types

**Pros:**
- âœ… Fewer bugs
- âœ… Better tooling
- âœ… Easier refactoring
- âœ… Self-documenting

**Cons:**
- âŒ More code to write
- âŒ Learning curve
- âŒ Build step required
- âŒ Can be verbose

lessons.codeExample:
// Real example: Types preventing bugs

// API response from server
const apiResponse = {
  user: {
    name: 'Alice',
    age: 25,
    // Note: email is missing!
  }
};

// Without types - bugs at runtime
function displayUserJS(response) {
  console.log(response.user.email.toLowerCase()); 
  // ğŸ’¥ Runtime error: Cannot read property 'toLowerCase' of undefined
}

// With types - caught at compile time
interface UserResponse {
  user: {
    name: string;
    age: number;
    email: string; // Required!
  };
}

function displayUserTS(response: UserResponse) {
  console.log(response.user.email.toLowerCase());
}

// âŒ TypeScript error at compile time:
// Property 'email' is missing in type
// displayUserTS(apiResponse);

// Another example: Array methods
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

// Without types - easy to make mistakes
const doubled = numbers.map(n => n * 2);
const result = doubled.toUppercase(); 
// ğŸ’¥ Runtime: toUppercase is not a function

// With types
const doubledTS: number[] = numbers.map(n => n * 2);
const resultTS = doubledTS.toUppercase(); 
// âŒ Compile error: Property 'toUppercase' does not exist on type 'number[]'

// Types guide you to the correct method:
// doubledTS.toString() âœ…
// doubledTS.join(', ') âœ…

// Node.js server example with Express

const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Middleware
app.use(express.json()); // Parse JSON bodies

// In-memory data (normally a database)
let users = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' }
];

// Routes
app.get('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);
});

app.get('/api/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const user = users.find(u => u.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (!user) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
  }
  res.json(user);
});

app.post('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  const newUser = {
    id: users.length + 1,
    name: req.body.name,
    email: req.body.email
  };
  users.push(newUser);
  res.status(201).json(newUser);
});

app.delete('/api/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const index = users.findIndex(u => u.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (index === -1) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
  }
  users.splice(index, 1);
  res.status(204).send();
});

// Start server
const PORT = 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});

